25|$|The classic fibula of the late-Roman era, and in {{fact the}} best known of all fibula types, is the {{crossbow}} type. The crossbow fibula consists of a highly arched semi-circular bow, usually of squarish cross-section, and a long flat foot. The fibula has a wide transverse bar (or arms) at the head containing the <b>pin-hinge.</b> Crossbow fibulae usually have three round or onion-shaped knobs: one at the head and one {{at each end of the}} transverse bar.|$|E

